# Analysis of different filter behaviors and their influence on input signals



AUDIO FILTERS AND EQUALIZERS ANALYSIS
==================================================
=== 1. SIGNAL BASICS ===
Signal: a function that carries information - usually changes over time
Time domain: representation of signal as a function of time
Frequency domain: representation of signal as a function of frequency

=== 2. FOURIER TRANSFORM ===
Fourier Transform converts a signal from time domain to frequency domain
Shows which frequencies are present in the signal and their strength

=== 3. FILTER TYPES ===
Filter: a system that changes the amplitude of different frequencies in a signal
Main types:
- Low-pass: passes low frequencies, blocks high frequencies
- High-pass: passes high frequencies, blocks low frequencies
- Band-pass: passes frequencies in a specific range
- Band-stop: blocks frequencies in a specific range

=== 4. FILTER COMBINATION ===
Filters can be combined for:
- Sharper cutoffs (steeper transitions)
- Complex frequency characteristics
- Improved filtering quality

=== 5. EQUALIZER ===
Equalizer: device that allows independent control of
gain in different frequency bands

=== CONCLUSION ===
Filters and equalizers are powerful tools for:
- Removing unwanted frequencies (noise, interference)
- Emphasizing important frequencies
- Correcting acoustic problems
- Creative sound shaping

In real applications, more complex algorithms are used
such as IIR and FIR filters, adaptive filters, etc.
